article.description:
Lisa Leslie had 19 points and the Los
Angeles Sparks scored the game's final 10 points to beat Utah 85-77
Friday night for a share of the Western Conference lead.
article.headline: Los Angeles scores last 10 points to win
article.linkText: Late rally helps Sparks tie Houston atop the West
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Lisa Leslie had 19 points and the Los
Angeles Sparks scored the game's final 10 points to beat Utah 85-77
Friday night for a share of the Western Conference lead.

	   Los Angeles, which matched Houston at a WNBA-best 23-7, held
Utah (19-11) without a field goal over the final 6:16.

	   Mwadi Mabika had 18 points and nine rebounds to help the Sparks
rebound from a 67-64 home defeat against Houston on Thursday night.

	   ''It was a very well-played game from the get-go,'' Los Angeles
coach Michael Cooper said. ''Especially after last night's loss it
was a game we easily could have turned over and lost this in the
first half.''

	   The Sparks were 32-for-63 (50.8 percent) from the field after
shooting a franchise-worst 25.7 percent against Houston in the game
that decided the playoff tiebreaker. Both Los Angeles and Houston
have two games remaining in the regular season.

	   ''It was very important to win tonight,'' Leslie said. ''We came
here without the option to lose.''

	   Marlies Askamp added a season-high 12 points for Los Angeles.
Marie Ferdinand scored 19 points for Utah and Adrienne Goodson
added 15 points and nine rebounds.

	   ''We know we can play with this team, we know we can beat this
team,'' Starzz coach Candi Harvey said. ''Hopefully, we'll get a
shot at them in the playoffs.''

	   After Ferdinand made a free throw with 3:20 remaining, Mabika
hit a jumper and Leslie followed a miss by Tamecka Dixon to give
the Sparks an 80-75 lead.

	   Utah led by 12 points and was 5-for-7 from 3-point range in the
first half. The Sparks tightened up their defense in the second
half and outscored the Starzz by 12.

	   ''At about midway through the second half we started giving them
transition baskets,'' Harvey said. ''You just can't give the Sparks
layups. They will kill you.''
